        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>This is primarily a continuum project, so we request maximum bandwidth (7.5 GHz per polarization).  To search for CO, we will allocate one band at the lowest spectral resolution, which will not result in any loss of continuum sensitivity.  If CO were associated with the millimeter ring, the expected rotational linewidth would be 5 km/s, easily resolved by the 1.3 km/s channel spacing of the lowest-resolution setting.  </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The diameter of the debris ring is 9", which will fit comfortably within the primary beam at Band 6.  The largest relevant angular scale in this image is the ~2" width of the ring estimated from Cycle 0 data (and to elucidate any larger angular scales associated with the disk major axis, short spacings observations from Cycle 2 have already been delivered).  This project is fundamentally a high-resolution experiment, hence the request for the extended configuration: the higher the resolution, the better the constraints we can place on masses and velocitieis in the disk. The chosen angular resolution of 0.25" provies the best balance between sensitivity and interesting angular scales, allowing us to measure the total mass of the large bodies dynamically stirring the debris belt down to a limit of roughly 2 Earth masses.  </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The total 1.3 mm flux in the debris ring measured by MacGregor et al. (2013) is 7.14 +/- 0.2 mJy.  Since the primary purpose of the experiment is to determine the spatial distribution of the flux, we make a conservative estimate based on the lowest surface brightness allowed by existing observational constraints.  In a worst-case scenario, the millimeter flux for AU Mic might be distributed over several arcseconds in radius (concentrated into the ~2"-wide ansae) and up to 0.6" FWHM vertically across the disk midplane (equivalent to the height measured in scattered light).  As a gross estimation, assuming that the 7.1 mJy of flux is spread uniformly into two 2x0.6 arcsec squares (one at each ansa) and resolved into 0.25" beams, this implies a required flux sensitivity of ~15 uJy/beam to achieve a signal-to-noise ratio of 10 per beam in Band 6.  To obtain a more realistic sensitvity estimate, we simulate an observation of an edge-on debris disk with properties similar to those of the AU Mic system and find that, for the full range of allowed vertical scale heights, sufficient signal-to-noise is achieved with a single hour (1.5h with overheads) in the extended configuration and half an hour (rms 26 uJy/beam) in a compact configuration.  The compact observations have already been delivered; we are requesting only to complete the extended configuration observations, of which 30% of the time has already been observed in Cycle 2.  </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
